Fantasy Premier League Data Analysis:¶

Tools to help your performance in FPL¶

Introduction

The goal of this tutorial is to use data to learn more about Premier League players' performances in FPL, to help people build their FPL teams. It is important to note that no metric used to differentiate player options will be objectively better to use than another. Some will be better in cases where the player is more knowledgeable about teams and players and thus is using their own insight on top of the data. Some will be better suited for those who are less knowledgeable and want to think less, just relying on the data given to make their decisions.

Note: this tutorial assumes a basic grasp of python, pandas, and requests.

Imports

Below we just import some packages we'll be using to retrieve, interact with, and visualize data.

In [274]:
import requests

Retrieval

Here, we want to access the Fantasy Premier League API. This is a straightforward process.

In [275]:
r = requests.get('https://fantasy.premierleague.com/api/bootstrap-static/')
r.json().keys()
Out[275]:
dict_keys(['events', 'game_settings', 'phases', 'teams', 'total_players', 'elements', 'element_stats', 'element_types'])

Data tidying

We can see various tables here. We will just be using the elements and element types. You will see why we use these particular ones. The other tables have useful information, but not for what we're looking at here, specifically.

At this point, we aren't gathering more data. What we're doing is taking the data we just retrieved and manipulating it. There are certain parts of the data we care about, and some we don't. This section is about putting what we care about in one place for easy access.

So, what data do we have here? We know player names, their position in the game (for now again, just a code), their current price in FPL (needs to be changed; the values should be divided by ten, they are shown here as integers, which they shouldn't be), how many minutes they've played this season, and how many points they've earned this season.

Let's now unencode the positions and fix the costs to be as they are in the game. To do the former, we must get another dataframe, just as we got this one, from the element_types table.

In [278]:
types = pd.DataFrame(r.json()['element_types'])

So, we can see here that the singular name is the actual position, and we can see the code (id column) they match in the players dataframe. So let's update the players object. Let's fix the costs too, while we're at it.

In [279]:
players['position'] = players.element_type.map(types.set_index('id').singular_name)

players['cost'] = players['now_cost']/10

Data Analysis

We now have just the data we want on our players, and can use it to make decisions about our FPL teams. Let's start by getting more interesting value from the data. For starters, let's create a column for points relative for cost. We will call this column "value_by_cost", as it represent, well, the player's value in points relative to how expensive they are in the game.

In [280]:
players['value_by_cost'] = players.total_points/players.cost

This is already useful, but how about a "value_by_minute column"? Maybe some players have played less, meaning they have less minutes, yet are scoring high. And maybe you happen to know they're going to play more now, whether because of injuries or players leaving/coming to their team. This is a metric that, as described in the introduction, would be more useful to those paying close attention to all these factors, as using this without knowing that may be pointless (they may do well in points per minute, but if they don't play, that's not going to be useful to your fantasy team).

We immediately notice many NaN's appearing, due to players who haven't had a single minute of game time this season. Given that by all metrics but cost these players have no data (0 minutes, 0 points, 0 value by either metric), let's drop them. Maybe you have some intuition that they will get a chance soon, but the data doesn't tell us anything about their potential value to your fantasy team regardless, as they have 0 points from 0 minutes. So, while they are not exactly examples of missing data, they are still something to be trimmed from our dataframe.

There's a problem apparent straight away. On both ends of the dataframe, we see players with less than a single full game weighted strongly in either direction. Now, we can weight things more favorably to people with more minutes, but that would kind of defeat the purpose of using this metric in the first place. I propose that we get rid of players with under 270 minutes (that's three full-length games). If you've played less than that, we are considering you not being used enough to draw any meaningful conclusion from your data. That seems reasonable to me.

In [284]:
players = players[players.minutes >= 270]
players.sort_values('value_by_minute', ascending=False)

Now, we have a table of data sortable by three useful metrics for performance (raw points, points based on cost, and points relative to time played). But this tool can be made more effective. Usually, when changing or creating your FPL team, you have specific gaps to fill. Maybe you're looking to replace a forward, for example. You can take this dataframe, sort by whatever metric you want, and look specifically at the top forwards. But why don't we make separate dataframes for different positions to make everyone's lives a little easier?

In [285]:
# note that we reset the index: this will be useful for making graphs later
goalkeepers = players.loc[players.position == "Goalkeeper"]
goalkeepers = goalkeepers.reset_index().drop('index', axis=1)
defenders = players.loc[players.position == "Defender"]
defenders = defenders.reset_index().drop('index', axis=1)
midfielders = players.loc[players.position == "Midfielder"]
midfielders = midfielders.reset_index().drop('index', axis=1)
forwards = players.loc[players.position == "Forward"]
forwards = forwards.reset_index().drop('index', axis=1)

We now have four dataframes, each corresponding to a different FPL position, with different metrics to judge players on based on your needs and knowledge levels (Do you know someone will be playing more now? If they are high up when sorting by points per minute, it may be worth buying them. Don't know about that and just want the highest earner on average? Just sort by points. Need to do that but worrying about overall cost of your team? Sort by value by cost.) We have created a a set of tables we can use to help us decide what FPL players to buy for our team based on our needs and knowledge.

Machine Learn- hey, this section is blank??

Yep. There are some valuable insights machine learning can give us, generally speaking. But my goal with this tutorial was not to use the data to predict how players will perform in the future and give insight in that sense. In fact, the whole points per minute thing was a step away from this; a step towards having FPL players using their own knowledge and insight in conjunction with the data we have to make their decisions. I have no doubt that using machine learning, we would not have seen Lingard (3rd best in the last table I explicitly showed above) as a viable option; prior to his move to his current team in January, he had played no games. Even after first few games, he would not be doing well in either raw points or value by cost (as he only had a few games to rack up points despite getting many in the games he had). And factoring in value by minute wouldn't be helpful either in a machine learning approach; Nketiah, who is higher than Lingard in the same table, is not a viable pick, as his lack of minutes are down to not playing well (by actual coach/fan standards, not fantasy point standards) rather than mitigating circumstances like injuries or a transfer to a new team. The other metrics neglect these circumstances, and while this one accounts for them, it doesn't just do that, it accounts for people who aren't playing much due to a perceived lack of talent. So a human insight into these things is sort of essential, for me. Without it, we can't simultaneously see the detriments of Nketiah and the value of Lingard, and I can't think of a conceivable way to truly consider these things systematically. And rather than implement something trivial for the sake of saying 'hey look, we did machine learning here', I want everything in this tutorial to be something I truly believe is meaningful and useful to any FPL player. Not something that is likely to be misleading.

Some visualization

Okay, having gone through all that, why don't we actually look at the data in graph form, so we can more clearly see the meaning behind all the work we did? For starters, let's look at how one's points per minute looks when plotted against one's cost. We will do this four times, once for each position. These graphs will show a player's performance based on the time they've played relative to their cost. This still relies on the intuition above to identify those whose points per minute may not be the best metric because their reasons for not playing too much are still relevant, however. I will be including a linear regression line in these plots, although I'm not sure the data suits one. At the end of the day, the higher and more leftward a player is, the better (as they will be the cheaper options who are performing well given the amount of time they've played), regardless of performance relative to some regression. And who knows, maybe the data will match that regression.

In [286]:
plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
sns.regplot(x='cost', y='value_by_minute', data=goalkeepers)

# code below adds labels so we can see which points on the graph correspond to what player
for i in range(goalkeepers.shape[0]):
    plt.text(x=goalkeepers.cost[i]+.05,y=goalkeepers.value_by_minute[i]+.001,s=goalkeepers.second_name[i], 
          fontdict=dict(color='white',size=10),
          bbox=dict(facecolor='black',alpha=0.5))
plt.title('Goalkeepers')
plt.show()

We can see from this plot (I realize the names overlap quite a bit in some areas) that the likes of Martinez and Mendy, while somewhat expensive, are statistically performing well given their gametime this season. Meanwhile, Becker, Lloris, and de Moraes are expensive yet underperforming by this metric. Meanwhile, the likes of Meslier and Forster stand out as good cheaper options (provided we look at the tables and see they have decent amounts of gametime this season or know from external knowledge they're set to play more from this point onwards). If I wanted to change my goalkeeper for my FPL team, I'd be leaning towards Martinez or Meslier, based on my budget and actual knowledge of the Premier League.

These plots rely on you, the reader, having some background knowledge in regards to things like that. For the sake of those less knowledgeable about such thigns but still enjoying playing FPL, I'll draw up plots comparing raw points to cost. I'll let the data for those plots speak for themselves rather than point out the outliers in terms of over- and under-performers, though.

Miscellaneous

Here are a few hypothetical scenarios we may find ourselves in, and how we can use what we've created to address them.

Scenario 1

Let's say you are disappointed with the returns one of your forwards is giving you. If you sell him, your remaining budget is 8.3. Let's see how you might go about picking his replacement.

87 Dias Belloli 2098 119 Midfielder 5.4 22.037037 0.056721

Conclusion

So, now that we've seen the data in a few different ways, what can we conclude? Well, for starters, from the plots we can see that in terms of raw points, expensive FPL options tend to do well. That's why, of course, they are so expensive. But looking at the data when normalizing the points based on the minutes players have had, we see a different result. We can see that identifying options who we can predict will be playing more frequently in the weeks to come, we may be able to actually outperform those popular, expensive options. If we know, for example, Carroll is likely to play this week for some reason, it may be worth taking him instead of Werner. Looking solely at the raw data, or what's available directly on the FPL site, it would be hard to come to this conclusion. Meanwhile, the above scenarios show some other practical application of the data we've gathered and metrics we've formed. The second in particular doesn't rely on outside information. And we can see here insights that we otherwise wouldn't. Harrison, for example, is a great cost-efficient option, as is Frello Filho. Those are not players you'd be likely to consider looking merely at raw data. The latter doesn't show up when sorting by raw points even in the top 20. Now we have the tools to take the FPL API and tweak some things to get valuable insight like this when it comes to forming our FPL teams.
